{"hits": {"hits": [{"created": "2024-08-29T11:55:26.902996+00:00", "modified": "2025-10-07T01:57:55.408534+00:00", "id": 13474845, "conceptrecid": "13474843", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.13474845", "conceptdoi": "10.5281/zenodo.13474843", "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.13474845", "metadata": {"title": "Oxidative damage varies in response to bacterial, fungal and viral antigen challenges in bats", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.13474845", "publication_date": "2023", "description": "(Uploaded by Plazi for the Bat Literature Project) The immune system plays an important role in defending against pathogens and regulating physiological homeostasis, but the strength of the immune responses depends on the type of pathogen. The immune system of bats shows a high variability in responsiveness towards various pathogens; they can safely harbor certain pathogens that are highly lethal to other mammals. Oxidative stress may act as a pathophysiological cellular mechanism mediating the immunological function of bats because of its potentially detrimental effects on physiological homeostasis, fertility and longevity. By experimentally exposing greater mouse-eared bats (Myotis myotis) to three antigens, it was previously shown that animals reacted immunologically most strongly to bacterial and viral antigens, but not to fungal ones. As a follow up, in this study we observed that both bacterial and fungal antigens induced a significant increase of plasma oxidative damage, whereas viral antigens did not cause any increase of plasma oxidative damage at all albeit the mild immune response. Thus, experimental bats were able to avoid oxidative stress only in the face of a viral antigen, possibly by dampening inflammatory signalling. Bats may be able to handle viral infections and live well beyond expectations by reducing the detrimental effects of molecular oxidation.", "access_right": "restricted", "creators": [{"name": "Costantini, David", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Schad, Julia", "